</div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1606174936829" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1606174936829"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;">Taking care of our health has always been a priority, but it’s making headlines now more than ever due to COVID-19 (coronavirus).&nbsp;</p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1606174903245" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1606174903245"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><font face="Montserrat"><span style="font-size: 35px; letter-spacing: 0.75px;"><b>1. Get Enough Sleep, but the Duration Isn’t the Only Thing That’s Important</b></span></font></p></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1606175073085" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1606175073085"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;">Sleep has been shown to be extremely helpful in our immune response.</p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;">We’re sure you’ve heard that sleep is vital to your well-being, especially getting 8-9 hours of sleep. While some of us can thrive on 5-7 hours of sleep and others need 8-9 hours, your body is the healthiest when you get a full 8-9 hours of sleep. But there’s a catch.</p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;">It’s not only the duration when you sleep, but the quality and time period of when you sleep. You want your sleep to line up with your natural circadian rhythm, which is the time you secrete the majority of melatonin – a great antioxidant that’s helpful to immune function. This happens between 9pm-6am, which will be the most beneficial on your immune system.</p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;">So, it’s important to go to bed during your normal sleep hours, even when it’s easy right now to sleep in or go to bed late.</p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1606175055110" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1606175055110"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p><font face="Montserrat"><span style="font-size: 35px;"><b>2. Exercise Benefits Your Health, but Only When It’s Done Appropriately</b></span></font></p></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1606174873787" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1606174873787"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-elm-left-sm gf-elm-left-xs" data-gemlang="en" data-exc=""><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;">Exercise is helpful for immune function, especially when it’s done appropriately.</p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;">Doing too many strenuous workouts such as intense long runs or HIIT workouts can actually deplete the body’s immune system. So, what’s right amount of exercise? Daily moderate exercise. You want something in between, a moderate workout that gets you sweaty and moving but doesn’t drain you at the end of the day.</p><p class="" style="font-size: 16px; font-family: Montserrat, sans-serif; text-align: start; color: rgb(28, 29, 29); letter-spacing: 1.3px;"><br></p></div></div><!--gfsplit--><div data-label="Text Block" data-key="text-block" id="e-1606175109988" class="element-wrap" data-icon="gpicon-textblock" data-ver="1" data-id="1606175109988"><div class="elm text-edit gf-elm-left gf-elm-left-lg gf-elm-left-md gf-el